data.content:
Yes, the arguments are swapped. In MSTest, `Assert.AreEqual` takes `(expected, actual)` — the expected (literal) value goes first, the actual (computed) result goes second.

Fixed:

```csharp
[TestClass]
public class MathTests
{
    [TestMethod]
    public void Add_TwoNumbers_ReturnsSum()
    {
        var result = Calculator.Add(2, 3);
        Assert.AreEqual(5, result);
    }

    [TestMethod]
    public void Multiply_ByZero_ReturnsZero()
    {
        var result = Calculator.Multiply(42, 0);
        Assert.AreEqual(0, result);
    }
}
```

This matters because when an assertion fails, MSTest reports: `Expected:<first arg> Actual:<second arg>`. With the original ordering, a failure message would confusingly say something like *"Expected: 6 Actual: 5"* instead of the correct *"Expected: 5 Actual: 6"*.
